===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|畾|宜}} – a pile.

Originally as {{zh-l|曡}}, with {{zh-l|晶}} on top. ''{{w|Shuowen}}'' commented that the shape change was promoted by the emperor of the short-lived {{w|Xin Dynasty}}, who deemed the use of three "suns" ({{zh-l|*日}}) in this character too empowering - compared to three "fields" ({{zh-l|*田}}).

===Etymology===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*g/l-t(y)ap||fold, layer, pile up, repeat}}. Cognate with {{och-l|摺|to fold}}, {{och-l|褶|lined dress}}, {{cog|bo|ལྟབ|t=to fold, gather up, to lay or put together}}, {{m|bo|ལྡེབ|t=to bend round or back, to turn round, to double down}}, {{m|bo|ལྡབ|t=to fold up, repeat, do again}}, {{cog|my|ထပ်|t=to stack, layer}} and {{cog|my|လိပ်||to fold up, to roll up}} (STEDT).

